data: {"type":"response.function_call_arguments.done","arguments":"{\"memory\":\"# Information Profile\\n- Title: Dolphin Research\\n- Some facts:\\n  - Fact 1: Dolphins are highly intelligent marine mammals known for their playful behavior.\\n  - Fact 2: They inhabit a variety of aquatic environments, including oceans, rivers, and estuaries.\\n  - Fact 3: Dolphins primarily eat fish, squid, and crustaceans, using echolocation to hunt.\\n- Summary: Dolphins are social animals that live in groups called pods, which can consist of a few individuals to over a hundred. They are known for their complex communication skills and social behaviors, such as cooperative hunting and nurturing of young. Most dolphins inhabit warm and temperate seas, but some species, like the Amazon river dolphin, are found in freshwater environments. Their diet mainly includes fish, which they catch using echolocation and coordinated efforts within their pods. \\n\\n## Dolphins' Behavior:\\n- Dolphins are known for their playful nature and love of socializing, often engaging in acrobatics and surfing waves.\\n- They use a variety of vocalizations, including clicks, whistles, and body language, to communicate with each other.\\n- Intelligent problem-solving skills have been observed, especially in hunting strategies and social interactions within pods.\\n\\n## Habitat:\\n- Dolphins thrive in diverse marine environments - from coastal areas and open oceans to rivers and estuaries.\\n- Some species are specifically adapted to freshwater habitats, like the Amazon river dolphin.\\n\\n## Diet:\\n- Dolphins are carnivorous, primarily consuming fish, squid, and crustaceans.\\n- They use echolocation to locate prey and often hunt cooperatively within pods, using various strategies to catch food.\\n\\n## Social Structure:\\n- Dolphins live in social groups known as pods, which vary in size and composition.\\n- Pods can be matrilineal, often led by older females who play a crucial role in the social dynamics.\\n- Social bonds are strong, with individuals often supporting one another in hunting and nurturing young.\"}","item_id":"fc_0d03993e795b18d6006a0aef3c74108195b81232fb89accb66","output_index":0,"sequence_number":420}

